            <div ng-click="showme3= !showme3">
              <div ng-show="showme3">
                <div class="row">
                  <div class="col-md-8">
                    <h4><p>The complex real-world problem that I strove to create a solution for was flooding in my basement; after the thawing of snow last spring, I experienced significant amount of water in my basement. I wanted to create a flood sensor that could detect water in my basement and then alert me. In order to build this system, I used a Raspberry Pi 3 Model B+ Ultimate Kit from CanaKit (CanaKit, n.d.). This kit is nice because it came with most of the supplies that I needed; including the CanaKit GPIO to Breadboard Interface Board, GPIO Ribbon Cable, Full-Size Large Breadboard, and multiple jumper wires, power adapter, microSD card, HDMI cable; all of which were necessary in the construction of my flood alarm (CanaKit, n.d.). In addition to these materials I also used a rain-water level sensor and Adafruit MCP3008 Analog to Digital Convertor (ADC). In order to get the Raspberry Pi to work I also had to have a computer screen, keyboard and mouse. Within the Raspberry Pi’s operating system, I used the Python coding language for programing of the water sensor (Amber, 2017; Rembor, n.d., Rototron, 2016). When the water sensor detects water, I used the website IFTTT
                    </h4>
                  </div>
                  <div class="col-md-4">
                    <img class="img-responsive" src="../img/jensite/singleboard_1.jpg">
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="row">
