                <div class="row">
                  <div class="col-md-8">
                    <h4><p>The first thing I did was plug the Raspberry Pi into my computer monitor with keyboard and mouse. In order to run the Raspberry Pi, I had to first make sure that it was configured with the Raspbian Operating System and all the coding tools for Python. Next, I attached the breadboard to the Raspberry Pi using the GPIO ribbon cable. To the breadboard, I attached the ADC chip, water-level sensor using jumper wires following instructions and schematic diagrams on the Adafruit Python and CircuitPython website (Raspberry Pi Foundation, n.d.-a; Rembor, n.d.). After trial and many errors, I was able to put together a python script that detected water by returning a value greater than 0 if water was detected by the water-level sensor (Amber, 2017; Rembor, n.d., Rototron, 2016). My next step was to device an alarm when water was detected. I decided to send a push message to my phone. Utilizing google I found IFTTT (IF This Then That) and Webhooks website that explained how to write a code in python to send an email based on set criteria (IFTTT, n.d.). I set up a free account on IFTTT and followed the instructions to get and add a request code to my existing python script (IFTTT, n.d.). I ran a test by placing my water sensor in a small cup of water and about two minutes later I received an email stating water had been detected. </p></h4>
